At the time this felt like a dubious move on my part, because the compensation I saw was going to require a lot of time. I felt like I was about to lose the initiative and this was the only way to keep it.

What I saw was that this move would force his King into a bad position, and if I could get my Knight to G6, the black king and this whole area would be stuck. So that's what I went for.

The major blunder of the game. Either he didn't see the double check or didn't realize where it could lead. I am still down two pieces for a pawn at this point, but there is light at the end of the tunnel. I see I can trade my two rooks and knight for his queen, bishop, and pawn. An even trade on points, but after that *all his pieces are out of position* and he will have a hard time defending his open king against my rapacious queen :D
